---
// The letter unfolds. The thesis as a short editorial passage in a single narrow
// column — the first thing you "read" once the seal is broken. Roman display,
// one italic pull-line for emphasis inside running copy (the sanctioned place
// for italic).
---
<section class="px-6 py-24 md:py-32" aria-labelledby="promise-heading">
  <div class="letter-column text-center" data-reveal>
    <h2
      id="promise-heading"
      class="display text-text text-[clamp(1.9rem,4.5vw,3rem)] leading-[1.2]"
    >
      A wax seal you can send as a link.
    </h2>
    <p class="font-body text-text-muted mx-auto mt-8 max-w-[40rem] text-[1.05rem] leading-[1.8] font-light">
      There is a moment when a guest opens your invitation, and it should feel like something. Paper
      captures it beautifully, but paper cannot carry a map, a guest list, or an RSVP. The usual
      digital invites carry all of that, and somehow feel like a form.
    </p>
    <p class="font-body text-text mx-auto mt-6 max-w-[40rem] text-[1.05rem] leading-[1.8] font-light">
      Cire is the third thing: an invitation that unwraps like the real one, greets each guest by
      name, and quietly does the work, counting every reply while your guests simply feel invited.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
